1
00:00:00,959 --> 00:00:30,696
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatu samma-sambhogasa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatu samma-sambhogasa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatu samma-sambhogasa

2
00:00:31,181 --> 00:00:35,067
homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:38,051 --> 00:00:50,210
So I'm slightly aware that my New Year address is directed at what is known in language teaching anyway, as false beginners.

4
00:00:51,652 --> 00:00:58,523
They are the ones who used to practice, stopped, and have now returned to the fold.

5
00:01:01,017 --> 00:01:09,810
So I have to make a special effort to enthuse you all, especially those, so that this will never happen again.

6
00:01:11,292 --> 00:01:26,112
And from this day on, until you slip into the warmth of the grave, you will continue to practice.

7
00:01:29,046 --> 00:01:35,213
As you know, many people come to meditation for various reasons, especially these days with this mindfulness movement.

8
00:01:36,575 --> 00:01:47,246
But the spiritual search, I think, begins when there is some sort of existential crisis, whether it's a very, very, very small sea or a sort of an earth-shattering one.

9
00:01:51,731 --> 00:01:59,019
And I think that's really, really where in the spiritual practice you have to put your

10
00:01:59,641 --> 00:02:27,588
your attention and the questions come up in various forms such as why am I here why is this here this whole universe was it here for why am I conscious why am I conscious of it all these sort of questions and worst of all why am I conscious of it and then I have to die just when I'm getting used to it just when I'm

11
00:02:28,497 --> 00:02:33,342
I start getting old and things happen.

12
00:02:33,361 --> 00:02:40,229
So these questions bring up in us all sorts of emotional reactions.

13
00:02:40,250 --> 00:02:46,957
And it's the investigation of that question, really, which is the spiritual quest.

14
00:02:46,978 --> 00:02:53,465
So in the Buddha's own terms, in his day, it was this awful idea that he kept coming back.

15
00:02:54,866 --> 00:02:55,667
Kept coming back.

16
00:02:55,706 --> 00:02:57,288
There's rounds of rebirths.

17
00:02:57,606 --> 00:03:26,567
and there seemed to be no escape from it it was a constant being born and then depending on your karma you ended up either as a dog or worse and sometimes as a king but those opportunities were very rare of course so it was the horror really of this rebirth which was seemingly one of the obsessions of the age

18
00:03:30,056 --> 00:03:34,942
And in a sense, if you're an annihilationist, that's a fate worse than death.

19
00:03:34,961 --> 00:03:36,002
You have to keep coming back.

20
00:03:36,864 --> 00:03:39,366
Sisyphus, I can't remember what he did.

21
00:03:39,567 --> 00:03:40,769
Does anybody remember what he did?

22
00:03:40,848 --> 00:03:42,030
He did something terrible.

23
00:03:42,711 --> 00:03:50,579
And his punishment was to roll this boulder up to the top of a hill and then to see it roll back down and then go back down and start again.

24
00:03:51,180 --> 00:03:51,721
And that was it.

25
00:03:51,741 --> 00:03:54,082
That was his life, you might say, in hell.

26
00:03:55,485 --> 00:03:59,389
So when we think of the spiritual quest,

27
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:03,224
We're really trying to answer these sort of deeper questions.

28
00:04:07,411 --> 00:04:18,807
And the Buddha's own quest led him to a particular answer, a particular experience that we call awakening or enlightenment.

29
00:04:20,468 --> 00:04:23,353
And from that moment onwards, he said, he didn't suffer.

30
00:04:23,814 --> 00:04:28,060
And then, of course, you have to define what he meant by this word dukkha.

31
00:04:30,250 --> 00:04:41,583
But as far as he was concerned, he always lived in a state of some joyous heart state, whether it was just pure equanimity, contentment.

32
00:04:42,644 --> 00:04:49,992
And when he was in relationship, it was either love, compassion, or joy.

33
00:04:50,012 --> 00:04:52,336
And remember that compassion is not a sad thing.

34
00:04:52,536 --> 00:04:54,077
Compassion is a joyful state.

35
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:58,923
If compassion leads you to some sort of morose state,

36
00:04:59,713 --> 00:05:29,247
state then something else has slipped in perhaps pity or grief but compassion is the joy that you get when you're helping people just knowing your limitations and that help might only be offering them goodwill you can only do so much today in some of the interviews this whole idea of what can you do the sort of modern western koan of

37
00:05:31,202 --> 00:05:33,826
After you've done everything you can do, what can you do?

38
00:05:36,307 --> 00:05:40,892
It's very difficult for us to accept that, the limitation of doing.

39
00:05:40,913 --> 00:05:45,098
So I always describe it as a ring of power around us.

40
00:05:46,278 --> 00:05:47,180
And that's all you can do.

41
00:05:47,199 --> 00:05:49,963
You can't go beyond what you can do.

42
00:05:50,783 --> 00:05:52,846
And then, of course, you can get other people to do things.

43
00:05:53,065 --> 00:05:54,728
That's your influence.

44
00:05:54,747 --> 00:05:56,350
Then after that...

45
00:05:56,954 --> 00:06:01,557
Trying to get beyond that is just frustration and depression and all sorts of things.

46
00:06:02,079 --> 00:06:02,579
Burnout.

47
00:06:09,065 --> 00:06:17,934
The whole idea of power, if you consider Tolkien, Lord of the Rings, you see.

48
00:06:17,954 --> 00:06:19,355
See if I've got the names right.

49
00:06:19,375 --> 00:06:21,137
Frodo, that's right.

50
00:06:21,156 --> 00:06:25,581
See, Frodo has this ring and Sauron, correct?

51
00:06:25,762 --> 00:06:26,201
Sauron.

52
00:06:26,569 --> 00:06:27,630
He wants this ring.

53
00:06:28,411 --> 00:06:29,934
And this is the ring of power.

54
00:06:30,774 --> 00:06:35,821
I mean, you can have all sorts of interpretations to Tolkien's story.

55
00:06:35,841 --> 00:06:38,644
But for me, this ring of power.

56
00:06:39,004 --> 00:06:42,369
And once Sauron had it, he would rule the whole of Middle-earth.

57
00:06:42,569 --> 00:06:44,992
Which is a horrible idea, as you know.

58
00:06:45,892 --> 00:06:51,098
So Frodo doesn't take on the power of that ring.

59
00:06:53,180 --> 00:06:55,564
He actually takes it to be destroyed.

60
00:06:56,589 --> 00:07:04,862
And in destroying all that sense of power and the sense of control and domination, wins him eternal life.

61
00:07:06,103 --> 00:07:17,521
Only because, not because he's upset Sauron and destroyed that potential, but because he himself has let go of all power and all desire for power.

62
00:07:18,802 --> 00:07:18,882
See?

63
00:07:18,903 --> 00:07:25,533
This is perhaps my own interpretation, you understand, but that's as I see it.

64
00:07:25,774 --> 00:07:26,074
And

65
00:07:27,690 --> 00:07:35,163
One of the things that the Buddha talks about is this whole idea of a self and what it means and how it comes to be.

66
00:07:36,805 --> 00:07:43,235
And when we talk about an existential crisis and we talk about why am I here, what consciousness is, what is it we're talking about?

67
00:07:43,396 --> 00:07:44,317
We always talk about me.

68
00:07:45,158 --> 00:07:48,966
The sense of me being conscious and me dying.

69
00:07:53,413 --> 00:07:54,153
And

70
00:07:55,028 --> 00:08:05,339
The whole idea of power in its bad sense is to be able to control the world, control our situation, so that me always feels safe.

71
00:08:07,182 --> 00:08:10,064
Me is always in charge, in control.

72
00:08:12,848 --> 00:08:16,452
And whenever that control slips from us, it's a horror story.

73
00:08:18,574 --> 00:08:23,600
And unless you're ready to let go of that desire for power, the wrong desire for power,

74
00:08:24,458 --> 00:08:29,564
or rather the desire for wrong power, it just becomes a battle.

75
00:08:31,187 --> 00:08:39,759
People who fight the idea of growing old, fight their situation, their loss.

76
00:08:41,461 --> 00:08:50,673
I always think of that, this is years ago now, of the policeman who was paralysed by a criminal.

77
00:08:51,855 --> 00:08:53,958
And he couldn't hack it, eventually he committed suicide.

78
00:08:55,727 --> 00:08:57,470
He was only paralysed from the waist downwards.

79
00:08:57,490 --> 00:09:00,114
He wasn't totally paralysed.

80
00:09:00,134 --> 00:09:06,162
But being a sports person and very active, he couldn't let go of that.

81
00:09:06,783 --> 00:09:11,028
And therefore it drove him to really seeing his life as useless, meaningless.

82
00:09:15,575 --> 00:09:21,322
So this idea of power, of control, is very much tied up with the self.

83
00:09:21,583 --> 00:09:23,405
Now, what does the Buddha do, you see?

84
00:09:23,960 --> 00:09:28,245
he makes the mistake of so many of his age, he tries to be happy.

85
00:09:29,586 --> 00:09:36,615
And he must have tried at home to be happy and found that the sensual pleasure was some wanting.

86
00:09:36,677 --> 00:09:38,938
It became vapid.

87
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:42,163
He didn't have any depth to it.

88
00:09:43,065 --> 00:09:45,427
So you have a good meal and that's the end of it.

89
00:09:47,691 --> 00:09:50,014
Sex, drugs and rock and roll, see they're vapid.

90
00:09:52,836 --> 00:09:53,258
And it's

91
00:09:53,845 --> 00:10:00,071
It's that weariness, the weariness which is trying to seek happiness and send your pleasure.

92
00:10:02,413 --> 00:10:04,635
The weariness of it.

93
00:10:05,057 --> 00:10:08,019
Just the sheer exhaustion of clubbing every night.

94
00:10:09,441 --> 00:10:12,384
You just can't take it anymore, you see.

95
00:10:14,807 --> 00:10:22,754
And then there was this other offering of the age, which was the jhana, the absorption stuff.

96
00:10:23,225 --> 00:10:25,167
Which you find in all religions.

97
00:10:25,187 --> 00:10:28,812
These beautiful states.

98
00:10:28,831 --> 00:10:29,493
Ecstatic.

99
00:10:32,255 --> 00:10:36,260
We can get that sort of ecstatic state by doing something extreme.

100
00:10:37,022 --> 00:10:41,407
By getting extreme sports and stuff like that.

101
00:10:41,788 --> 00:10:43,188
Or getting lost in music.

102
00:10:43,629 --> 00:10:46,352
Just for that moment there where we lose a sense of self.

103
00:10:47,153 --> 00:10:52,640
And we're totally absorbed into the extremely joyous state.

104
00:10:53,633 --> 00:11:19,977
that sort of happiness is again very it's very fulfilling if it's wholesome it's very fulfilling but it passes so in the end again there's a sort of weariness and if we compare that to the jhana then we find ourselves in a similar situation

105
00:11:21,982 --> 00:11:26,086
The jhana, the absorptions are self-generated.

106
00:11:26,388 --> 00:11:27,908
You don't need anything outside you.

107
00:11:29,691 --> 00:11:37,940
The metta that we do, if you just keep practicing that, you'll see slowly but surely this beautiful state arises in you.

108
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:40,643
I'm sure you've experienced it.

109
00:11:40,663 --> 00:11:42,806
And the more you do it, the stronger that state is.

110
00:11:43,687 --> 00:11:50,474
And it gets so strong that, as it were, you fall into it and you lose the sense of somebody doing the metta.

111
00:11:50,614 --> 00:11:51,534
There is just

112
00:11:51,937 --> 00:11:53,337
The lovely state that you're in.

113
00:11:53,958 --> 00:11:54,820
It's an absorption.

114
00:11:54,980 --> 00:11:58,322
That's why they call it an absorption.

115
00:11:58,342 --> 00:12:02,626
We do it on a much, shall we say, obvious level when you're watching a film.

116
00:12:03,827 --> 00:12:07,150
So when you're watching a good film, for that two hours, you're lost.

117
00:12:08,432 --> 00:12:10,333
There's not somebody watching the film.

118
00:12:10,354 --> 00:12:15,378
There's a loss of that somebody, that self, that self-awareness that's just the film.

119
00:12:16,139 --> 00:12:18,160
And then when you come out, you arrive again.

120
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:19,100
You arise.

121
00:12:19,782 --> 00:12:20,863
You say, oh, that was fantastic.

122
00:12:22,565 --> 00:12:48,807
and that absorption is a type of happiness and it can become more and more refined as you practice these other more religious forms prayer, mantra, even coloured circles in Theravada they have 40 of these particular subjects which can lead you to various depths but again

123
00:12:49,345 --> 00:12:52,948
It's a happiness which is dependent on conditions.

124
00:12:53,208 --> 00:13:00,076
It's a happiness which is dependent on your body, your mind, whatever you're using.

125
00:13:00,837 --> 00:13:03,821
It's dependent on somebody giving you food, things like that.

126
00:13:04,501 --> 00:13:05,423
It's always dependent.

127
00:13:05,743 --> 00:13:08,285
And therefore, you don't have total control.

128
00:13:08,686 --> 00:13:10,168
And worse, it comes to an end.

129
00:13:10,227 --> 00:13:11,308
You can't sit there forever.

130
00:13:15,474 --> 00:13:18,677
So there was always something which didn't satisfy you.

131
00:13:18,977 --> 00:13:21,200
And as you know, he got very good at it.

132
00:13:21,441 --> 00:13:22,981
He was invited to teach.

133
00:13:24,443 --> 00:13:26,144
But he just didn't hack it, you see.

134
00:13:27,346 --> 00:13:35,654
And I presume, although he doesn't say this, one has to interpret it a little bit, that after a while, he had that same sort of weariness.

135
00:13:36,556 --> 00:13:42,422
You know, I'm not another jama.

136
00:13:42,501 --> 00:13:44,985
There must have been something unsatisfying about it.

137
00:13:45,024 --> 00:13:47,888
Because for the others, for the ones who were following that path,

138
00:13:48,424 --> 00:13:49,606
They didn't leave.

139
00:13:49,626 --> 00:13:51,649
They didn't say, you know, I'm fed up with this.

140
00:13:51,889 --> 00:13:53,030
They were really into it.

141
00:13:53,532 --> 00:13:56,615
Just developing these beautiful mental heart steps.

142
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:08,731
And then he goes into another form of practice which was prevalent at the time, which was this self-mortification.

143
00:14:08,751 --> 00:14:17,283
And I presume that even then he's practicing jhana, but here the problem was the body itself because it was understood that

144
00:14:17,803 --> 00:14:25,073
by some at that time, the Jains for instance, your karma expressed itself in your physicality.

145
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:27,197
Your body was your karma.

146
00:14:27,236 --> 00:14:30,741
It was like a physical thing which held on to your soul.

147
00:14:30,802 --> 00:14:34,586
And if you could let go of the body, then the soul would rise.

148
00:14:35,087 --> 00:14:39,693
Of course you had to work out all the karma that you'd accumulated through past births.

149
00:14:41,856 --> 00:14:44,159
I met a Jain actually the other day.

150
00:14:44,200 --> 00:14:47,625
I'd heard about this, but he confirmed it for me.

151
00:14:48,095 --> 00:14:52,320
That the Jain saint is the one who finally determines to stop eating.

152
00:14:54,022 --> 00:14:58,246
And he says when somebody does that in the Jain community, he's like divine.

153
00:14:58,527 --> 00:15:02,390
I mean, he's suddenly become somebody of enormous importance.

154
00:15:02,851 --> 00:15:10,681
And he actually has the courage to let go of this life form and then rise into, his soul to rise into heaven.

155
00:15:13,945 --> 00:15:16,126
I don't know, we don't know whether the Buddha...

156
00:15:17,272 --> 00:15:23,240
believed that particular theory, although the Jain leader was his contemporary, elder contemporary.

157
00:15:24,260 --> 00:15:29,989
We can presume it, but at some point he found it also just more suffering.

158
00:15:30,009 --> 00:15:32,893
That's what he said, just more suffering.

159
00:15:32,913 --> 00:15:34,235
It somehow didn't work for him.

160
00:15:36,037 --> 00:15:43,346
Again, we don't know the mental processes that he went through, but he definitely found it wearisome,

161
00:15:43,647 --> 00:15:46,210
And useless, that's what he calls it, useless.

162
00:15:46,470 --> 00:15:49,072
He doesn't say it's unprofitable, he says it's useless.

163
00:15:49,092 --> 00:15:50,414
Profitless.

164
00:15:50,434 --> 00:15:52,417
And so that's when he leaves, remember, you see?

165
00:15:52,437 --> 00:15:53,097
That's when he leaves.

166
00:15:54,038 --> 00:15:59,504
So up until now, we could say that he's trying to steal from heaven, like us all.

167
00:15:59,524 --> 00:16:09,537
We're trying to grab something from the eternal life through our own personal effort, through a personal effort of gaining, attaining, controlling,

168
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:14,541
And as you know, he's despairing.

169
00:16:14,561 --> 00:16:15,461
He's by the roadside.

170
00:16:15,523 --> 00:16:16,464
He wonders what to do.

171
00:16:19,609 --> 00:16:21,913
And then he gets this wonderful gift from Sujata.

172
00:16:22,072 --> 00:16:23,315
You remember the rice pudding?

173
00:16:25,498 --> 00:16:30,405
Which has amazing effects, as you know.

174
00:16:30,426 --> 00:16:34,493
So this vivifies him.

175
00:16:34,692 --> 00:16:40,501
And he has this memory, remember, of a childhood where he's watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

176
00:16:41,798 --> 00:17:10,911
and he recognises that state as a child as being the same as the Jhanic states that he was in with an extra component which was that sense of curiosity that's the point where he actually becomes self-enlightened before that he's just following the paths that the society were offering him and finding them you know, weren't satisfactory and now he has this insight

177
00:17:11,666 --> 00:17:22,557
instead of trying to grab happiness and trying to hold it, find it, keep it, he now turns upon the suffering and asks the question, why do I suffer?

178
00:17:23,318 --> 00:17:27,182
His whole meditation, as it were, turns around on itself.

179
00:17:27,202 --> 00:17:29,204
And it's with that new inspiration that he sits.

180
00:17:29,265 --> 00:17:35,711
And he seems to have been so inspired by that and seems to have thought of it as, well, there's nothing else but this now.

181
00:17:37,011 --> 00:17:41,656
And he makes this great determination not to rise either

182
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:45,243
you know, to crack the problem or die.

183
00:17:47,006 --> 00:17:52,833
So, I mean, I always say, very lucky for him, lucky for us, he sort of cracked it.

184
00:17:52,853 --> 00:17:57,679
And in a sense, he opened up the gates, the gate of the deathless, that's what it's called.

185
00:17:57,699 --> 00:17:59,540
He opened up the gates to the deathless.

186
00:18:01,284 --> 00:18:08,792
And if you think of anything that people do in the world, there's always somebody, there's always somebody who makes it first.

187
00:18:09,173 --> 00:18:12,116
You know, somebody climbs Everest and everybody gets up there.

188
00:18:13,902 --> 00:18:15,604
Nobody wants to get up there.

189
00:18:15,663 --> 00:18:22,773
As soon as it's made available by one human being, it's made available to everybody.

190
00:18:22,794 --> 00:18:26,798
So when he opened this gate to the deathless, he opened it for everybody.

191
00:18:26,959 --> 00:18:33,708
Anybody who wants to liberate themselves from suffering is there to be taken.

192
00:18:33,729 --> 00:18:42,339
And fortunately, he had this great ability to teach, which meant that he laid down a very clear path as to how we actually make it.

193
00:18:42,775 --> 00:18:46,059
So it wasn't just a theory, it wasn't just an idea, a philosophy.

194
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:50,727
In fact, he wouldn't really rate it as a philosopher at all.

195
00:18:51,468 --> 00:18:55,153
He was more of a psychologist, an ethical psychologist.

196
00:18:55,834 --> 00:19:09,773
And he laid down a real specific practice, which we term right awareness or vipassana and words like that, is it?

197
00:19:09,794 --> 00:19:10,335
So...

198
00:19:10,770 --> 00:19:12,894
There's this path that he's laid out.

199
00:19:13,955 --> 00:19:14,737
And he puts it.

200
00:19:15,317 --> 00:19:17,099
He centers on a particular.

201
00:19:18,382 --> 00:19:18,843
Mental.

202
00:19:19,123 --> 00:19:19,683
A mental.

203
00:19:22,107 --> 00:19:22,627
Quality.

204
00:19:22,667 --> 00:19:24,310
This quality of desire.

205
00:19:26,554 --> 00:19:27,234
Which is where.

206
00:19:27,295 --> 00:19:29,739
Which he calls the cause of suffering.

207
00:19:29,878 --> 00:19:34,285
The cause of suffering.

208
00:19:34,885 --> 00:19:36,949
Desire is the cause of suffering.

209
00:19:36,969 --> 00:19:39,011
He talks about the three avenues.

210
00:19:39,051 --> 00:19:39,613
The three.

211
00:19:39,880 --> 00:19:44,765
the three perspectives, the three characteristics of existence.

212
00:19:44,785 --> 00:19:48,148
That there is impermanence, everything is impermanent.

213
00:19:49,170 --> 00:19:55,457
That there is nothing in the world which is going to ultimately, completely and fully satisfy us.

214
00:19:55,537 --> 00:19:56,198
That's the dukkha.

215
00:19:56,919 --> 00:19:59,821
And that the idea of a self is an illusion.

216
00:20:00,542 --> 00:20:07,170
It's not that you don't need the illusion of a self, but it is knowing it.

217
00:20:07,420 --> 00:20:10,364
what the illusion, or better still, the delusion is.

218
00:20:11,265 --> 00:20:18,693
So these are the three gates, you might say, or the three avenues of investigation, but the fundamental cause is desire.

219
00:20:20,276 --> 00:20:22,898
The psychological fundamental cause is desire.

220
00:20:25,221 --> 00:20:29,487
And this desire, when you think about it, is about power.

221
00:20:29,507 --> 00:20:35,554
It's about us wanting those things that are going to make me happy.

222
00:20:37,001 --> 00:20:38,503
And having control over them.

223
00:20:38,523 --> 00:20:41,208
Whether it's by money or just naked power.

224
00:20:44,011 --> 00:20:48,219
And it's about getting rid of all those things that are undermining my happiness.

225
00:20:51,083 --> 00:20:53,487
Just annihilating enemies.

226
00:20:53,646 --> 00:20:55,269
Anybody whom I don't like.

227
00:20:57,732 --> 00:20:58,733
I like to annihilate.

228
00:20:59,035 --> 00:20:59,976
Get rid of completely.

229
00:21:00,056 --> 00:21:05,163
And then surely I'll be completely happy.

230
00:21:05,183 --> 00:21:05,845
So that's

231
00:21:06,095 --> 00:21:14,944
If you look at desire from the point of view of controlling the environment, controlling our environment, in order to make it something that is making me happy.

232
00:21:16,067 --> 00:21:17,669
I'm always seeking this happiness.

233
00:21:18,209 --> 00:21:20,832
And of course people define happiness in all sorts of ways.

234
00:21:20,852 --> 00:21:25,317
It can be riches, it can be hanging about, it can be sleeping, let's say.

235
00:21:25,337 --> 00:21:35,088
It doesn't matter how you define happiness, but we're always trying to manipulate the situation in order to make ourselves comfortable

236
00:21:35,305 --> 00:21:37,007
And at best, happy.

237
00:21:37,027 --> 00:21:43,476
It's about power.

238
00:21:43,496 --> 00:21:46,701
Now that's what he points out as the cause.

239
00:21:47,442 --> 00:21:49,384
The cause of suffering is desire.

240
00:21:49,545 --> 00:21:50,445
This wrong desire.

241
00:21:50,705 --> 00:21:55,492
It's not a wrong desire to want to escape suffering, let's be right in it.

242
00:21:56,713 --> 00:22:02,021
The desire is to seek happiness in the sensual world.

243
00:22:02,041 --> 00:22:04,484
By which we mean a permanent happiness.

244
00:22:05,056 --> 00:22:11,786
The fleeting happinesses of sensual pleasure, the joys of relationship, the joys of nature, fine.

245
00:22:12,527 --> 00:22:30,653
But these even there, we twist it, trying to hold it, trying to maintain it, trying to squeeze this, the last pip out of the orange, the last little drop of juice.

246
00:22:30,673 --> 00:22:32,174
So it's that, and that's the attachment.

247
00:22:32,194 --> 00:22:32,615
Attachment.

248
00:22:33,067 --> 00:22:35,109
so what is attachment?

249
00:22:35,171 --> 00:23:01,843
attachment is this very desire this very psychological dependency on something over which we're trying to control but which we can't for happiness it's a really wrong it's a really painful investment of our energy a useless investment of our energy then you might ask well okay

250
00:23:02,126 --> 00:23:04,469
Because I'm still on this existential business.

251
00:23:04,489 --> 00:23:05,190
Why am I here?

252
00:23:05,931 --> 00:23:07,813
Why am I doing that?

253
00:23:08,432 --> 00:23:15,861
Why am I trying to manipulate the world and trying to seek some sort of permanent happiness?

254
00:23:18,143 --> 00:23:26,290
Now when I dig deeper, I find that we come to this essential delusion about the self.

255
00:23:26,310 --> 00:23:32,116
The self is an identity

256
00:23:33,008 --> 00:23:34,609
It's an identity.

257
00:23:34,630 --> 00:23:38,593
There's no such thing as a self because the identity keeps shifting.

258
00:23:40,654 --> 00:23:44,459
So when I was a child, my identity was very much with the body.

259
00:23:45,460 --> 00:23:49,363
Three, four, well, up until teenage, I suppose.

260
00:23:49,383 --> 00:23:50,183
I am the body.

261
00:23:52,967 --> 00:23:57,431
Then maybe around about teenage, I don't know, you start being emotion.

262
00:23:57,911 --> 00:23:59,492
I am my emotions.

263
00:23:59,553 --> 00:24:02,796
I'm identifying with emotions as separate from the body

264
00:24:04,057 --> 00:24:05,779
And thought.

265
00:24:05,799 --> 00:24:07,282
I am the thinker.

266
00:24:07,303 --> 00:24:08,384
I am thought.

267
00:24:08,423 --> 00:24:09,685
Who am I if I can't think?

268
00:24:13,411 --> 00:24:17,656
And the identity shifts from moment to moment depending on what you're experiencing.

269
00:24:17,676 --> 00:24:22,163
So if you happen to be having a cup of tea, then you're a physical self.

270
00:24:23,125 --> 00:24:30,315
If you happen to be sitting there musing about your existential crisis, then you're a thought self.

271
00:24:30,335 --> 00:24:31,737
If it's emotional, emotional self.

272
00:24:31,987 --> 00:24:37,894
So this self isn't something that exists outside your experience.

273
00:24:38,215 --> 00:24:41,579
It is a relationship you're having with the experience.

274
00:24:41,599 --> 00:24:46,006
And that relationship is being defined as me.

275
00:24:46,026 --> 00:24:53,376
And me.

276
00:24:53,396 --> 00:25:01,587
Now when we sit in meditation, when we sit in vipassana, we bounce out of, we pull ourselves out of that enmeshment

277
00:25:02,597 --> 00:25:28,268
and we discover a different me within ourselves that we call the observer the feeler, the one who knows and suddenly all those things that before I thought were me become objects to observe, to feel I'm distancing, I'm pushing out of, I'm lifting into a different orbit within myself

278
00:25:29,547 --> 00:25:46,428
And it may be that in so doing that, you suddenly realise actually, in that position of the observer, at least for a few moments during every sitting, you are in fact liberated from the body, heart and mind.

279
00:25:46,448 --> 00:25:51,354
You are liberated from painful emotions because you're looking at them.

280
00:25:51,374 --> 00:25:56,500
It doesn't make them any less painful in themselves, it's just that you're no longer entrapped by

281
00:25:56,884 --> 00:26:04,692
And you're no longer caught up in all the mentation, the stories that they make the mind develop.

282
00:26:10,278 --> 00:26:18,226
And in that position, you realize that you don't have the power that you thought you had.

283
00:26:19,646 --> 00:26:22,650
So the body, the knee begins to hurt.

284
00:26:23,891 --> 00:26:25,692
Whether you want it to or not, it just hurts.

285
00:26:27,107 --> 00:26:29,430
And if you say, stop hurting, nothing happens.

286
00:26:29,871 --> 00:26:30,451
It gets worse.

287
00:26:30,471 --> 00:26:34,535
And if you fight it, it gets even worse.

288
00:26:34,714 --> 00:26:38,798
And emotion comes up.

289
00:26:38,818 --> 00:26:39,599
You didn't ask for it.

290
00:26:40,019 --> 00:26:40,740
It just arose.

291
00:26:40,840 --> 00:26:41,461
And there you have it.

292
00:26:42,201 --> 00:26:43,222
It might be anxiety.

293
00:26:43,242 --> 00:26:44,765
It might be joy for it.

294
00:26:44,785 --> 00:26:46,787
It could be something lovely for a change.

295
00:26:48,288 --> 00:26:49,249
And it just arises.

296
00:26:49,269 --> 00:26:49,729
And you're there.

297
00:26:49,749 --> 00:26:50,470
You're watching it.

298
00:26:50,529 --> 00:26:51,090
And it's come.

299
00:26:51,111 --> 00:26:51,951
And you're feeling it.

300
00:26:51,971 --> 00:26:52,791
You know it's there.

301
00:26:52,852 --> 00:26:56,675
And if you say, go away, it won't.

302
00:26:56,909 --> 00:27:24,064
it'll keep on coming you can avert your attention you can leave the meditation room and go for a run or something but you can't while you're in that state and something arises you've pulled out of it you're in a different orbit for want of a better word but you're actually releasing control actually releasing control you're actually beginning to drop

303
00:27:24,347 --> 00:27:28,614
this dreadful ring into the furnace of destruction.

304
00:27:32,078 --> 00:27:33,981
And it's being comfortable with that.

305
00:27:34,262 --> 00:27:50,727
It's being able to realise or to see or to experience that actually there is a place where we can find within ourselves that is temporarily liberated from all the stuff that goes on within us.

306
00:28:00,005 --> 00:28:20,048
And then you realize that when you re-enter into the psychophysical organism that it is this very knowing which is it's within the very knowing that the distortion is to be found.

307
00:28:20,690 --> 00:28:22,352
There's a way of seeing.

308
00:28:22,692 --> 00:28:23,753
We're seeing things.

309
00:28:23,874 --> 00:28:27,218
We are understanding things in a wrong way.

310
00:28:27,617 --> 00:28:29,099
And that's what the problem is.

311
00:28:30,176 --> 00:28:31,439
The problem isn't the body.

312
00:28:32,138 --> 00:28:33,401
The problem isn't the heart.

313
00:28:34,142 --> 00:28:35,343
The problem isn't the mind.

314
00:28:36,545 --> 00:28:43,512
It's somehow our engagement in this psychophysical organism which isn't right.

315
00:28:43,532 --> 00:28:44,453
Which is warped.

316
00:28:45,736 --> 00:28:46,876
There's something wrong with it.

317
00:28:49,861 --> 00:28:56,910
And that something wrong with it is the identity with this very psychophysical organism.

318
00:28:56,930 --> 00:28:59,593
Because when I say to myself I am

319
00:29:00,890 --> 00:29:01,651
Bodhidharma.

320
00:29:02,672 --> 00:29:04,153
I am that, you see.

321
00:29:04,855 --> 00:29:08,598
Then it's in this form that I'm trying to seek happiness.

322
00:29:11,382 --> 00:29:12,903
See.

323
00:29:12,923 --> 00:29:15,307
And that's what we're always seeking at all times.

324
00:29:15,326 --> 00:29:17,789
We're always at all times seeking happiness.

325
00:29:18,069 --> 00:29:19,771
Even if it's the happiness of oblivion.

326
00:29:20,712 --> 00:29:25,578
Even if you get so fed up with things you launch yourself into the bed and disappear.

327
00:29:26,099 --> 00:29:27,320
You're still seeking happiness.

328
00:29:27,622 --> 00:29:28,061
You know.

329
00:29:32,310 --> 00:30:01,692
so the process of awakening the process of enlightening ourselves is to catch where the warp is to catch where the distortion is coming the vipalasa as it's put vipalasa means to see things as permanent or to think they can be permanent when they're not or at least they'll stay similar and they never do

330
00:30:03,157 --> 00:30:08,945
To find, to try and seek happiness in something which is not going to deliver.

331
00:30:08,965 --> 00:30:15,875
And to see something substantial which doesn't have any substance.

332
00:30:16,076 --> 00:30:19,140
Especially internally, the sense of self.

333
00:30:20,402 --> 00:30:21,403
The sense of me.

334
00:30:31,458 --> 00:30:41,326
So when we practice vipassana, which is the core practice, and it's from there that we take awareness into daily life, etc., etc., there's your core practice.

335
00:30:41,366 --> 00:30:59,663
The morning, when you enter into that state, even if it's only for a short time, you're reminding yourself of this higher way of being in the world, which is the observer, the feeler, the knower, the one who knows.

336
00:30:59,682 --> 00:31:00,604
And even though

337
00:31:01,174 --> 00:31:06,761
there is even then a distortion because that's also a false sense of self.

338
00:31:07,803 --> 00:31:17,515
At least we're telling ourselves every time we do that, we're somehow getting the message across that we're not this physical, this psychophysical organism.

339
00:31:17,535 --> 00:31:21,160
That's the message we're constantly telling ourselves.

340
00:31:21,180 --> 00:31:29,190
And when we're in the state of the observer, something very strange is happening because there is a knowing that there's a knower

341
00:31:31,042 --> 00:31:34,366
Now, what does that, what's that telling us?

342
00:31:34,847 --> 00:31:41,156
It's telling us that this self, this self-awareness is somehow pointing in the right direction.

343
00:31:44,560 --> 00:31:47,285
Just like in a mirror, it's pointing in the right direction.

344
00:31:48,385 --> 00:31:51,931
It's a sense of that knowing within the mind.

345
00:31:53,773 --> 00:32:00,122
But just as the mirror distorts our image, so this sense of the observer is also a distortion.

346
00:32:04,557 --> 00:32:09,422
But it's a much better place to be than a physical self, or an emotional self, or a thought self.

347
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:12,944
It's a much wiser place to be.

348
00:32:12,964 --> 00:32:20,093
And what we hope is that in accessing that in the morning, and we remind ourselves of this position.

349
00:32:20,452 --> 00:32:27,941
It can be a reflection, but actually the doing of it, the doing of it is an experience which stays with us.

350
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:33,365
And the more we do it, the more we become aware of that position of being the observer.

351
00:32:35,422 --> 00:32:39,265
Liberates us from entering into delusions.

352
00:32:40,445 --> 00:32:45,931
Which is offered by the body, heart and mind.

353
00:32:45,951 --> 00:32:47,632
Or better expressed.

354
00:32:48,012 --> 00:32:51,816
Which arises because of our identity with the body, heart and mind.

355
00:32:55,719 --> 00:32:58,280
So here in meditation when pain comes.

356
00:33:00,363 --> 00:33:01,663
And you see the reaction.

357
00:33:02,744 --> 00:33:03,905
You want to move.

358
00:33:03,925 --> 00:33:04,727
Why should I suffer this?

359
00:33:04,767 --> 00:33:05,326
All that sort of stuff.

360
00:33:05,964 --> 00:33:32,074
and you stay with that reaction the reaction is coming from this self that wants to manipulate the world to make it always comfortable or happy but if you stay with that two things are happening first of all this reaction begins to die away so the old habit of trying to control is being undermined and secondly you are reinforcing

361
00:33:33,116 --> 00:33:37,082
A new identity of being that which is not the body, heart and mind.

362
00:33:41,748 --> 00:33:47,515
And in the same way, when an emotion comes up, it's a nasty one, we don't want to feel it.

363
00:33:48,115 --> 00:33:51,859
See, somebody's emailed me about toxic shame.

364
00:33:52,300 --> 00:33:57,007
I mean, real heavy shame that goes back to childhood or something.

365
00:33:57,027 --> 00:33:58,669
And how destructive it is, you know.

366
00:34:00,303 --> 00:34:06,849
And he was saying to me that it was a good job that he did get into drugs, otherwise he would have killed himself.

367
00:34:07,892 --> 00:34:08,893
It was so painful.

368
00:34:09,432 --> 00:34:16,400
And it's only now that slowly but surely he's able to turn on this dreadful feeling of shame.

369
00:34:18,903 --> 00:34:25,871
Every time he's in company, he feels people can penetrate him, can see the way he really is, which is, you know,

370
00:34:28,146 --> 00:34:32,030
And to be able to stay with that, you see.

371
00:34:32,050 --> 00:34:35,434
So that's undermining this reaction of not wanting.

372
00:34:36,775 --> 00:34:37,594
Having control.

373
00:34:37,956 --> 00:34:40,577
Trying to manipulate things.

374
00:34:40,597 --> 00:34:44,681
It's the growth of patience, the being able to bear, to bear with.

375
00:34:44,702 --> 00:34:52,688
And it's also the ability, or should we say, the growing realization that there is something above the shame.

376
00:34:52,748 --> 00:34:54,250
There's something beyond the shame.

377
00:34:55,311 --> 00:34:57,072
The observer, the feeler, the knower.

378
00:35:04,849 --> 00:35:15,164
And as an aside to that, something which happens as a consequence, quite naturally, unwittingly you might say, the heart's healing itself.

379
00:35:16,766 --> 00:35:25,860
So two things we realise through our meditation practice is that when an emotion catches the mind and creates a story, it's developing itself.

380
00:35:26,681 --> 00:35:27,481
I mean you know that.

381
00:35:27,884 --> 00:35:35,034
Every time you get angry, somebody says something nasty to you, you repeat it a hundred thousand times to make yourself even more and more angry.

382
00:35:36,896 --> 00:35:38,318
And seek true revenge.

383
00:35:39,760 --> 00:35:42,583
See?

384
00:35:42,603 --> 00:35:45,889
So we know that we have to stop the mind creating stories.

385
00:35:47,630 --> 00:35:56,202
And when an emotion is releasing itself as a physical sensation, as a felt state,

386
00:35:56,925 --> 00:36:00,851
it's actually expending its energy.

387
00:36:02,534 --> 00:36:05,518
It needs an active act of will to develop.

388
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:11,889
And even when the mind slips away in one of these little stories, there's been a little empowerment there.

389
00:36:12,148 --> 00:36:15,974
Even though it's habitual, there's been little empowerment.

390
00:36:15,994 --> 00:36:25,009
And if you're not careful, that's why we can spend hours in meditation thinking about how we're going to kill somebody.

391
00:36:27,806 --> 00:36:28,327
Or worse.

392
00:36:29,148 --> 00:36:29,648
Or worse.

393
00:36:30,590 --> 00:36:33,454
So when you realize that, you come back, you see.

394
00:36:33,574 --> 00:36:47,351
And then if we can just stay with an emotional state long enough to see it dissipate, no matter how painful that is, that's when we get the confidence of being able to stay with this stuff.

395
00:36:47,391 --> 00:36:50,916
Because then we begin to realize that actually that's the process of healing.

396
00:36:51,135 --> 00:36:51,856
That's the setup.

397
00:37:03,110 --> 00:37:08,034
So now we have to return to this essential question as to, you know, why am I here in the first place?

398
00:37:08,054 --> 00:37:10,556
I mean, this is the new year, if I can say.

399
00:37:10,577 --> 00:37:24,630
So I should be making new resolutions and lifting up my heart of courage and all that, you know, shield and sword and into the fray and all that sort of stuff.

400
00:37:24,650 --> 00:37:28,853
So returning to our question, you know, why are we here?

401
00:37:29,454 --> 00:37:32,998
Well, in terms of some sort of theology

402
00:37:33,231 --> 00:37:42,023
in terms of some sort of grand philosophy, the Buddha is characteristically quiet.

403
00:37:42,043 --> 00:37:43,764
And I think there are two reasons for this.

404
00:37:44,666 --> 00:37:51,434
First of all, once you go beyond personal experience, you're into inference.

405
00:37:51,454 --> 00:37:57,101
But secondly, the experience of Nibbana is total and complete.

406
00:37:58,643 --> 00:38:00,505
It doesn't have a reason beyond itself.

407
00:38:04,112 --> 00:38:10,682
When we were doing the standing meditation, just being, just drawing our attention into the present moment.

408
00:38:12,786 --> 00:38:18,074
And just for one moment letting go of a reason for being, a reason beyond itself.

409
00:38:20,197 --> 00:38:22,340
And a future that we have to plan.

410
00:38:25,365 --> 00:38:29,833
Planning is also a form of control.

411
00:38:30,757 --> 00:38:32,119
I mean, there's good control, remember.

412
00:38:32,260 --> 00:38:35,724
I mean, if you've got to go to the dentist, you have to control events to get there on time.

413
00:38:36,905 --> 00:38:39,867
You don't want to miss a dental appointment.

414
00:38:39,887 --> 00:38:43,172
But just for a moment there, every so often, to just stop.

415
00:38:45,295 --> 00:38:46,735
And just be with the moment.

416
00:38:46,755 --> 00:38:49,539
Just be with the sensuality of the moment.

417
00:38:50,059 --> 00:38:51,541
Bury yourself into the body.

418
00:38:51,842 --> 00:38:54,445
Just being here.

419
00:38:54,905 --> 00:38:57,188
And that's where you get this sense of timelessness.

420
00:39:00,577 --> 00:39:02,320
So it's the mind that creates time.

421
00:39:02,619 --> 00:39:08,688
It's the mind which creates this idea of movement in time.

422
00:39:09,329 --> 00:39:10,931
It's a mental construct.

423
00:39:11,273 --> 00:39:16,039
Actually, as we all know, you only exist in this present moment.

424
00:39:16,059 --> 00:39:20,425
Which doesn't deny the fact that you've got to plan and all that sort of stuff.

425
00:39:21,007 --> 00:39:28,557
But it's just every so often during the day to stop and remind ourselves that there is...

426
00:39:29,467 --> 00:39:31,568
A different mode that we can enter.

427
00:39:31,809 --> 00:39:35,713
Just this pure being.

428
00:39:37,635 --> 00:39:43,641
Just because we're self-aware in that moment, it's still getting the message across.

429
00:39:43,961 --> 00:39:45,282
Still getting the message across.

430
00:39:45,784 --> 00:39:47,585
That there is two modes.

431
00:39:47,746 --> 00:39:49,467
One of being and one of doing.

432
00:39:50,228 --> 00:39:51,750
They don't cancel each other out.

433
00:39:52,210 --> 00:39:56,594
But if you're always doing, you're missing out on the being.

434
00:39:56,614 --> 00:39:57,576
And that's our problem.

435
00:39:57,596 --> 00:39:58,697
We're always doing something.

436
00:40:04,280 --> 00:40:07,344
Now when you're just being, there's no control.

437
00:40:08,385 --> 00:40:09,686
Because there's nothing to control.

438
00:40:10,208 --> 00:40:11,228
You're in the present moment.

439
00:40:11,329 --> 00:40:13,092
It arises and passes away.

440
00:40:13,112 --> 00:40:13,371
That's it.

441
00:40:16,335 --> 00:40:20,481
So there, we're getting a hint of the Buddha mind.

442
00:40:24,106 --> 00:40:33,780
And coming back to the position of the observer, when you're in that state in your meditation, and it's pretty clear to you that you are orbiting

443
00:40:34,250 --> 00:40:43,664
that you've pulled yourself out of, the body with its sensations, the heart with its emotions, and the mind with its thoughts and images.

444
00:40:43,684 --> 00:40:50,914
When you've been in that state for a while, and you come out of it, and you reflect upon it, just ask yourself, what is inside the observer?

445
00:40:50,954 --> 00:40:54,199
What's it made of?

446
00:40:54,219 --> 00:40:57,202
Are there any sensations there?

447
00:40:57,222 --> 00:40:59,186
Are there any emotions there?

448
00:40:59,646 --> 00:41:01,068
Any emotional states at all?

449
00:41:02,311 --> 00:41:03,311
Is there any thought there?

450
00:41:03,864 --> 00:41:04,666
Thought patterns.

451
00:41:07,548 --> 00:41:14,577
So we're obviously beginning to experience something which is not phenomenal.

452
00:41:15,097 --> 00:41:22,045
It's not something which is arising and passing away.

453
00:41:22,065 --> 00:41:29,193
And when you've come out of that state, and it's been very clear to you, ask yourself, was it satisfying?

454
00:41:31,315 --> 00:41:32,876
Because the Buddha says, and I

455
00:41:33,362 --> 00:41:35,485
And I shall leave you with this.

456
00:41:35,505 --> 00:41:39,152
Those who are mindful are in the presence of Nibbana.

457
00:41:39,172 --> 00:41:40,974
In the presence, in the vicinity of it.

458
00:41:41,074 --> 00:41:43,056
That's how close we are.

459
00:41:43,077 --> 00:41:48,344
It's as though we are looking into it and not being aware of that state.

460
00:41:55,675 --> 00:42:00,382
And then you realize why all spiritual practice anyway

461
00:42:01,239 --> 00:42:03,983
in all these traditions, always moves towards silence.

462
00:42:04,443 --> 00:42:08,047
It always moves towards some sort of silence.

463
00:42:11,733 --> 00:42:23,146
So another approach is to just develop that taste for calmness, a taste for silence, a taste for non-doing, without letting the mind just go off on its own.

464
00:42:33,606 --> 00:42:40,155
Now that position has also got some relationship to what it is that you're experiencing.

465
00:42:40,175 --> 00:42:43,039
Whether it's physical, emotional or mental.

466
00:42:43,059 --> 00:42:44,922
It has the relationship of non-attachment.

467
00:42:47,144 --> 00:42:50,389
Of not grasping, of not wanting to have power.

468
00:42:50,409 --> 00:42:51,251
That's the relationship.

469
00:42:51,271 --> 00:42:55,936
Because you're watching it, you're investigating it.

470
00:42:55,956 --> 00:42:56,036
See?

471
00:42:56,056 --> 00:43:02,144
So now, when we re-enter into the psychophysical organism, you see,

472
00:43:02,563 --> 00:43:29,398
and through that into the world of action we find very slowly that we're actually undermined that whole idea of controlling we're undermining the idea of trying to manipulate things and that brings us round to that sense of contentment which is wanting what one has not always trying to get what one wants

473
00:43:32,467 --> 00:43:34,148
And you start from there, you see.

474
00:43:34,168 --> 00:43:35,831
You start from this is the way it is.

475
00:43:37,233 --> 00:43:38,954
Which doesn't undermine potential.

476
00:43:40,096 --> 00:43:47,465
It's just that you're starting off from a realistic base before you would have normally tried to manipulate things.

477
00:43:49,568 --> 00:43:50,668
This is the way it is.

478
00:43:52,771 --> 00:43:55,554
So a neighbour of ours, he fell out of bed.

479
00:43:57,797 --> 00:44:00,581
And slipped his disc really badly.

480
00:44:01,061 --> 00:44:01,882
He was in a wheelchair.

481
00:44:03,094 --> 00:44:06,699
And I met his wife, who's a delightful, lively woman.

482
00:44:08,201 --> 00:44:09,503
And she's moaning about him.

483
00:44:09,543 --> 00:44:12,686
She's saying, you know, I've got to do this and I've got to do that.

484
00:44:13,047 --> 00:44:16,132
And then she says this lovely phrase, she says, it shouldn't be like this.

485
00:44:17,092 --> 00:44:17,833
And I said, ah.

486
00:44:18,313 --> 00:44:20,777
I said, yeah, there we are, you see, that's where the suffering is.

487
00:44:21,277 --> 00:44:23,920
That it shouldn't be like this.

488
00:44:25,382 --> 00:44:31,050
I think it's in the film, what's his name, Clint Eastwood, Unforgiven.

489
00:44:31,070 --> 00:44:31,311
Yeah?

490
00:44:31,331 --> 00:44:31,431
Yeah.

491
00:44:31,967 --> 00:44:35,873
And at the end, Clint, he kills them all.

492
00:44:35,893 --> 00:44:46,306
And as he dies, this terrible, nasty, sadistic sheriff, can't remember his name, he's a great actor, remember his name?

493
00:44:46,367 --> 00:44:49,030
He says, just before he goes, he says, it shouldn't have been like this.

494
00:44:53,697 --> 00:44:58,282
He said, how many times do we, you know, in the day say, it shouldn't be like this.

495
00:44:58,302 --> 00:44:58,903
It shouldn't rain.

496
00:44:59,204 --> 00:45:00,726
I mean, damn it, I've come here on retreat.

497
00:45:01,297 --> 00:45:01,918
It should be nice.

498
00:45:03,998 --> 00:45:07,902
And she shouldn't cough like that.

499
00:45:08,262 --> 00:45:09,103
And what's the meaning of that?

500
00:45:09,143 --> 00:45:12,766
Why is the door clicking like that?

501
00:45:13,947 --> 00:45:16,670
It's all this business of trying to manipulate, control.

502
00:45:17,391 --> 00:45:22,155
Now, it's not as though understanding this, that it's all going to stop.

503
00:45:22,494 --> 00:45:23,735
Oh, if heaven did, only it would.

504
00:45:26,219 --> 00:45:29,121
But at least now we're not fooled by it.

505
00:45:29,141 --> 00:45:31,302
That's the point, not to be fooled by it.

506
00:45:31,789 --> 00:45:35,394
So we know as soon as we hear the phrase, it shouldn't be like this.

507
00:45:35,996 --> 00:45:36,456
Aha!

508
00:45:36,476 --> 00:45:40,141
So you say, Mara, I see you.

509
00:45:40,181 --> 00:45:40,521
That's it.

510
00:45:40,882 --> 00:45:45,108
No longer it has the power to upset our contentment.

511
00:45:45,347 --> 00:45:46,289
This is the way it is.

512
00:45:47,190 --> 00:45:51,916
It's a lovely little phrase to repeat to ourselves.

513
00:45:51,936 --> 00:45:54,239
And remember that's not the same as resignation.

514
00:45:54,280 --> 00:45:55,782
Resignation is a despair.

515
00:45:56,043 --> 00:45:57,704
This is the way it is, I can't do anything.

516
00:45:57,724 --> 00:45:59,347
If this is the way it is, what can be done?

517
00:45:59,847 --> 00:46:00,007
It's

518
00:46:00,358 --> 00:46:09,463
Grounding ourselves in the way it is without coming to a situation, coming to a moment, coming to a relationship with prejudice, expectation.

519
00:46:11,007 --> 00:46:11,748
Expectation.

520
00:46:12,911 --> 00:46:13,193
Preference.

521
00:46:13,213 --> 00:46:13,454
Preference.

522
00:46:14,315 --> 00:46:14,757
Preference.

523
00:46:26,684 --> 00:46:41,318
So I've bumped around here and there and all over the place, but I hope that you get this idea of a central control panel called the self that really just wants to be happy.

524
00:46:41,717 --> 00:46:42,139
That's all.

525
00:46:42,338 --> 00:46:44,541
Just want to be happy.

526
00:46:44,561 --> 00:46:47,804
And it's trying to constantly manipulate the situation.

527
00:46:49,266 --> 00:46:53,670
Holding on to, grabbing what makes it happy.

528
00:46:54,358 --> 00:46:56,041
And pushing away, annihilating.

529
00:46:56,061 --> 00:46:57,682
And if it gets too much, run for it.

530
00:46:58,844 --> 00:47:06,614
So those are your three main attitudes that arise out of the self.

531
00:47:07,657 --> 00:47:08,538
Aggrandizement.

532
00:47:09,798 --> 00:47:10,619
Accumulation.

533
00:47:12,342 --> 00:47:12,943
Aversion.

534
00:47:14,105 --> 00:47:14,666
And fear.

535
00:47:15,387 --> 00:47:16,748
Those are your basics.

536
00:47:16,768 --> 00:47:22,476
And from out of these three snakes, yes, arise all our miseries.

537
00:47:23,840 --> 00:47:28,264
So it really is beginning to see that in our daily life.

538
00:47:28,284 --> 00:47:32,168
Slowly but surely, cutting away, cutting away, cutting away.

539
00:47:32,188 --> 00:47:39,635
Roshi Kennett, who was, you know, she started the Zen order in the West.

540
00:47:40,195 --> 00:47:42,597
Thostelol Abbey, some of you might know, lovely place.

541
00:47:44,458 --> 00:47:51,365
She talked about the practice of being a huge granite mountain, which you had to shift, and all you had

542
00:47:52,695 --> 00:47:56,221
was a little teaspoon.

543
00:47:56,240 --> 00:48:09,478
So, getting across that this, you know, it's not easy, but, you know, we should contemplate on the benefits of our practice and how it's helped us in our lives.

544
00:48:10,259 --> 00:48:18,849
And that, in a way, is a sort of self-encouragement, you know, and it makes you want to give a bit more, do a bit more.

545
00:48:18,869 --> 00:48:21,132
And this doing is always arising out of

546
00:48:21,534 --> 00:48:24,237
That lovely sense of calmness.

547
00:48:25,139 --> 00:48:28,822
One of the facts of enlightenment.

548
00:48:28,842 --> 00:48:30,364
Don't put a time slot on it.

549
00:48:30,625 --> 00:48:32,827
An expectation.

550
00:48:32,847 --> 00:48:36,731
So remember there's a distinction to be made between hope and expectation.

551
00:48:37,813 --> 00:48:49,525
The hope that arises from the practice is something which comes to us because we begin to see, we can perceive that there is an end to suffering.

552
00:48:49,545 --> 00:48:50,648
I mean that's what the practice is about.

553
00:48:50,688 --> 00:48:50,967
It's about

554
00:48:51,150 --> 00:48:55,336
actually perceiving how we can actually become fully liberated.

555
00:48:57,179 --> 00:48:58,199
That's the hope.

556
00:48:58,221 --> 00:49:00,943
The expectation is when we put a date on it.

557
00:49:01,925 --> 00:49:02,425
Then we've had it.

558
00:49:03,387 --> 00:49:05,530
Then there's sheer frustration and despair.

559
00:49:07,012 --> 00:49:14,983
So it's not good to think of practice too much anyway, in terms of progress, because it's very much up and down.

560
00:49:15,724 --> 00:49:20,871
So this year we might start off with a firm commitment to up the practice a bit,

561
00:49:22,387 --> 00:49:24,528
Get up to Sadi Panya to do a four-week retreat.

562
00:49:27,913 --> 00:49:33,297
Why are you all laughing?

563
00:49:34,460 --> 00:49:36,601
To get up there and do some extra work, you see.

564
00:49:36,882 --> 00:49:39,324
And then, you know, next weekend you're drunk.

565
00:49:39,344 --> 00:49:42,307
And you wake up and, oh, come on, do that.

566
00:49:42,327 --> 00:49:42,728
What is it?

567
00:49:43,108 --> 00:49:44,889
So it goes up and down.

568
00:49:44,990 --> 00:49:47,233
But it's keeping the nose in the right direction.

569
00:49:47,974 --> 00:49:49,255
Keeping your nose in the right direction.

570
00:49:51,547 --> 00:49:58,472
And very slowly over time one sees the effect of the practice.

571
00:49:58,492 --> 00:50:00,414
But don't put milestones on it.

572
00:50:01,195 --> 00:50:03,177
Oh boy, that's wicked.

573
00:50:04,217 --> 00:50:05,798
Putting milestones on your practice.

574
00:50:05,938 --> 00:50:06,940
I should be here now.

575
00:50:07,181 --> 00:50:09,503
Why have I not been doing this?

576
00:50:09,663 --> 00:50:11,244
I've been doing this for 30 years.

577
00:50:11,284 --> 00:50:15,527
Why am I not aware all the time?

578
00:50:15,547 --> 00:50:16,568
37 years, let me say.

579
00:50:17,750 --> 00:50:19,351
My mind's still going all over the place.

580
00:50:20,192 --> 00:50:20,271
See?

581
00:50:20,291 --> 00:50:20,371
See?

582
00:50:20,842 --> 00:50:22,605
I mean I should be in a state of despair.

583
00:50:22,985 --> 00:50:24,206
Anybody should be.

584
00:50:24,226 --> 00:50:25,168
In this room anyway.

585
00:50:27,652 --> 00:50:28,672
But it's a case of.

586
00:50:29,034 --> 00:50:29,855
You know you just keep.

587
00:50:30,114 --> 00:50:30,556
Just keep.

588
00:50:31,197 --> 00:50:31,617
Just keep.

589
00:50:31,998 --> 00:50:32,858
Taking the next step.

590
00:50:33,059 --> 00:50:36,925
Taking the next step.

591
00:50:36,945 --> 00:50:38,527
So hopefully tomorrow.

592
00:50:38,547 --> 00:50:40,449
I'll give you some.

593
00:50:41,411 --> 00:50:43,014
Some template that you can work on.

594
00:50:43,275 --> 00:50:44,717
To reflect upon your life.

595
00:50:44,737 --> 00:50:46,139
Which you may or may not want to use.

596
00:50:47,621 --> 00:50:48,402
And.

597
00:50:49,951 --> 00:50:53,356
And try and build up some sort of resolutions for the year.

598
00:50:53,697 --> 00:50:55,239
One, two, not too many.

599
00:50:56,240 --> 00:51:02,030
And I've got to work out a little ritual which I would normally do at the stupa at the centre.

600
00:51:02,692 --> 00:51:03,492
A burnt offering.

601
00:51:03,813 --> 00:51:06,737
So I'll try and work something out with Mark.

602
00:51:07,199 --> 00:51:08,440
He'll be the carrier of the flame.

603
00:51:10,804 --> 00:51:14,389
And we'll try and organise just a little ritual.

604
00:51:14,409 --> 00:51:17,275
Putting little bits of paper into a bowl and setting fire to it.

605
00:51:18,114 --> 00:51:23,284
Burnt offerings, burnt offerings.

606
00:51:23,304 --> 00:51:26,168
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

607
00:51:26,550 --> 00:51:35,264
May you, by your renewed commitment and invigoration of the path, reach the end of suffering sooner rather than later.

608
00:51:37,309 --> 00:51:41,996
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

